at nostalgic life of the first postwar decades is being swept aside by radical forces from the Lubavitcher at one end to Reform and feminism at the other. What started in 1945 as a “remnant” community has become a dynamic new center of Jewish life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHolocaust survivorszGermany. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1945-1990. 0aJews, East EuropeanzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030009271440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013312740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300133127/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY